HK University of Science, Hong Kong

HKUST-Division of Life Sciences-BMI Scientific Exchange Programs

 

 

In July 17th, 2013, The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology  (HKUST) and the EPFL signed a strategic partnership agreement to strengthen academic and research collaboration between the two institutions. The scope of the partnership cover, but not limited to, the following areas; 1) exchange of faculty and scholars; 2) Exchange of students; 3) Co-operation in research and the presentation of its results; 4) Joint organization of seminars, workshops and other; 5) exchange of academic materials, publications and other scientific information; 6) Other educational and academic exchange activities to which both universities agree.

The Division of Life Science at HKUST offers rigorous and competitive undergraduate and postgraduate programs. Currently, we have 487 undergraduate students and 180 postgraduate students. Currently, the Division has 36 full-time faculty members with significant expertise in the areas of neuroscience, structural biology, cell & developmental biology, marine & environmental biology, and biotechnology. The Division is the home of the State Key Laboratory of Molecular Neuroscience, the only one at HKUST and one of the twelve in Hong Kong. In addition, the Division has a large collection of the state-of-the-art major equipment and is a major stakeholder of the Biosciences Central Research Facility (BioCRF).  The Division offers research-oriented graduate programs leading to the Master of Philosophy (MPhil) and Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) degrees in Life Science, with or without a concentration in Molecular Medicine.

Joint Activities

1st HKUST-SV-BMI Joint Symposium
Lausanne, March 14-15, 2014

2nd HKUST-SV-BMI Joint Symposium
Hong Kong, December 14-15, 2015

 Research Internship Programs offered by HKUST

International Visiting Internship Student Program (IVISP): To promote diversity, the University provides sponsorship to international visiting interns under the International Visiting Internship Student Program. The International Visiting Internship Student Program supports international students from institutions outside Hong Kong to come to HKUST to engage in the research work under the supervision of top-notch faculty for a period of 2 - 6 months. Besides gaining valuable research experience in a new environment, students may also enjoy a rewarding cultural exchange experience in Hong Kong. Read More…

HKUST summer research program at UST (2017): The HKUST International Summer Exchange Program (ISP) allows students from partner institutions to study at HKUST during our summer term as exchange students. In Summer 2016, HKUST welcomed over 250 exchange students from our partner institutions.  Read More…

News
Mrs Jin Teng Chung, bachelor student from HKUST, received a 6 months fellowship for a research visit at the BMI in the frame of the International Research Enrichment Program (IRE), supported by the Division of Life Sciences at HKUST and co-funded by the Laboratory of Neuroenergetics and Cellular Dynamics (Magistretti lab) at the BMI. She conducted a project focusing on the role of astrocytic glycogen metabolism in sleep-wake regulation.

 

 

“My internship experience in LNDC, BMI was fruitful and enjoyable.

The working environment was friendly and welcoming despite the language and culture differences. I have learned a lot of laboratory soft and hard skills from the people I worked with. I believe that this will help me a lot in my academic and research pursuits in neuroscience in the future.

The city is pretty, the lake is stunning, weather is nice, cheese is good, chocolate is yummy, people are polite… I can never ask for more!“

BMI & Partners Annual PhD Students Neuroscience Symposium

As part of its effort to promote and enhance collaboration with its strategic partners, the BMI is organizing an annual PhD students’ symposium that will bring together PhD students from the BMI and its strategic partnering institutions. The symposium aims to provide the students with a forum to share their work, exchange ideas, explore collaborations, expand their network and discuss career and scientific topics of mutual interest. Read more...

 

International Student Exchange Program of the Brain Mind Institute

As part of its effort to promote and enhance scientific collaborations with its strategic partners, the BMI is launching an exchange program aimed at supporting master students from the BMI and partner institutions. Read more...

To apply:

Documents to be upload in PDF format (please indicate your last name at the beginning of each docs uploaded) :

• CV
• Statement of motivation
• Copy of your transcripts (grades)
• 1 Page description of the project
• 2 Recommendation letters (can also be sent by email to Prof. H. Lashuel: hilal.lashuel@epfl.ch)

Please fill out the application form and upload the requested documents here.
